<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-040-184 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 479 175</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  Oct 3 1991 v36 n20A p3(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fast-framing cameras surpass RS-170; at Electronic Imaging/East.andO;(RS-170 video rate standard)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Vaughan, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Electronic Imaging/East trade show, to be held in Oct 1991, isexpected to see the debut of a number of products that help tomake the video camera a more viable proposition as a computerinput device.andP;  These products include 'fast-framing' cameras,which operate above traditional RS-170 video rates and improvetiming-resolution by taking frames more often.andP;  Such camerasinclude EGandamp;G Reticon's MC4256, which offers a 256 by 256-pixelarray sensor and can feed 480 frames-per-second directly into amicrocomputer.andP;  Dalsa Inc's CA-D1-0512 camera offers 512 by512-pixel resolution and 730 frames/second.andP;  Such capabilitiesexceed the limits of standard frame grabber circuitry.andP;  AdaptiveOptics is expected to debut the ICP-160 image processor/universalfast-frame buffer to fill the gap.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   EG and G Inc. EG and G Reticon Corp. (Product development)Dalsa Inc. (Product development)Adaptive Optics Associates (Product development).andO;Ticker:    EGG.andO;Product:   EG and G Reticon MC4526 (Video camera) (Product development)Dalsa CA-D1-0512 (Video camera) (Product development)Adaptive Optics ICP-160 (Circuit board) (Product development).andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentBoards/CardsVideo camerasI/O devicesImage processing.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Cameras break out of &quot;RS-170 box&quot; -- the route to extended video.andO;(chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>